Special note on Substrate node
______________________________
Most the components from the technology library have an hidden node
that represents the substrate below the device. This is a "connect
by name" type of connection where a parameter on the device defines
the connectivity for the substrate.

* For n-type devices, this is commonly the local p-type substrate
    (pbulk/pwell or isolated pwell).

* For p-type devices, this is commonly the local n-type substrate
    (nwell or deep nwell).

* For passive devices, the node will be named "sub" but it refers to
the local substrate, which will be the nwell or pwell.

---------------
Implementation
---------------
In newer kits, the connection uses Cadence's Inherited Connections
flow where the value of the parameter can be set at any point in the
hierarchy. See below for details on how to set this parameter.

In older kits, the connection uses a CDF parameter. The value
of the CDF parameter is copied to the Inherited Connection parameter.

For the schematic and layout to match, all of the nodes in the same substrate
must be connected together.

------------------------------------------------------
Instructions for using Cadence's Inherited Connections:
------------------------------------------------------
Cadence provides functionality to allow the user to determine available
inherited expressions and their values. Detailed documentation on the
Inherited Connections Flow is available in the Cadence Virtuoso documentation.

 To access available inherited connection information please follow these steps:

* Open a schematic in the Virtuoso Schematic Editor

* Set up the session to identify the inherited properties:
  Select the Options->Editor menu item. Set the schematic editor options
  view lists to include a view like "spectre" that includes inherited
  terminals.  For example, set the view list to:
spectre schematic symbol

* View or set the inherited properties of an instance or a hierarchy:
To see the available properties on an instance or hierarchy:
- Select the menu item Edit->Net Expressions->Available Properties
- Click on the desired device from the schematic window. The form will
  show all netSet property names available, as well as the current value
  of those properties.
- If you click on a primitive, you will see the properties available and
  their currently evaluated value.
- If you click on a non-leaf cell, but all lower cells have netSets,
  you will not see any available properties.
- You can choose to override the property using the other buttons on the form.

To see the properties down the hierarchy:
- Select the menu item Edit->Net Expressions->Evaluated Names
- Click on the instance with hierarchy
- The form will display all the names/values down the hierarchy and
  also show the point in the hierarchy tree where these values are set. 

